om","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rhys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Rees  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Rice  .","German: habitational name from a place in the Rhineland called Rees.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Andreas  ."]}]},{"name":"Gethin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 18;2007: 39; 2010: NA)","Welsh: from the personal name <i>Gethin</i>, perhaps a soft-mutated form of <i>cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Getting","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of   Gethin  .","Welsh: Anglicized form of the personal name <i>Gutyn</i>, a pet form of <i>Gruffudd</i> (see   Griffith  ), mainly found in north Wales.","German: very rare variant of   Gettig   or <b>Götting</b> (see   Goetting  ) and, in North America, also an altered form of the latter."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Rhys Gethin was born about 1390, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Rhys ap Llywelyn and Angharad Holland. He had at least 2 sons with Joan ferch Hywel."},"et":{"about 1390–":"umbes 1390–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1410–Male"